<p><strong>American Badger (<em>Taxidea taxus</em>)</strong></p>
<p><strong>Family: </strong>Mustelidae<br />
<strong>Genus Species: </strong><em>Taxidea taxus</em><br />
<strong>Common Name: </strong>American Badger<br /><p>
<p><strong>Identification</strong></p>
<p>The American Badger has a body length of 18-22 inches, a tail length of 4-6 inches, and a weight of 13-25 pounds. It has a heavy body, short legs, a yellowish-gray color with a median white stripe from the nose over the top of its head, white cheeks, and a black spot in front of each ear. It also has black feet, extremely long claws on the front, and a yellowish belly and short tail. Sometimes seen along highways in early morning. For a more detailed overview of this species see 〔<a href="http://www.enature.com/fieldguides/detail.asp?allSpecies=y&amp;searchText=american%20badger&amp;curGroupID=5&amp;lgfromWhere=&amp;curPageNum=1" target="_blank">eNature</a>〕.</p>
<p><strong> </strong></p>
<p><strong>Habitat Associations and Natural History</strong></p>
<p>The badger resides in open grasslands and deserts. It is mostly nocturnal, but often seen during the day, especially in the morning. It is a great digger; it digs out small rodents, which it preys on. It dens in burrows that it made, and has been shown to live 12 years in captivity. It bears 2-5 young in February-May.</p>
